{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:18:26.222833+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 3b0f2572474ab4ac8636eb4d2b4974a3159686d8)", "id": "lc_e3177750-09cd-4087-a008-949f01b17dd0"}, {"type": "text", "text": "\"\"\"Token-bucket rate limiter backed by a Redis Lua script.\"\"\"\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom importlib import resources\nfrom typing import Tuple\n\nimport redis\n\n\n_SCRIPT = resources.files(\"ratelimit_redis\").joinpath(\"bucket.lua\").read_text()\n\n\nclass Limiter:\n    def __init__(self, redis_url: str, capacity: int, refill_per_sec: float) -> None:\n        self._r = redis.Redis.from_url(redis_url, decode_responses=False)\n        self._capacity = capacity\n        self._refill = refill_per_sec\n        self._sha = self._r.script_load(_SCRIPT)\n\n    def check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]:\n        bucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"  # hash-tag for cluster compatibility\n        result = self._r.evalsha(\n            self._sha,\n            1,\n            bucket_key,\n            str(self._capacity),\n            str(self._refill),\n            str(cost),\n        )\n        allowed = bool(result[0])\n        remaining = int(result[1])\n        return allowed, remaining\n", "id": "lc_2300b39b-ce67-4d1e-9d13-81bd24f26c93"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "edd97df1-c9f3-445f-85f4-49481a73a851", "tool_call_id": "call_9ad93515eaf44a11bf21863e", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:18:26.379305+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 39f9dd70b04b84aafe72caf640fd6a1ccdfee39f)", "id": "lc_f4cd180a-291a-48e6-a744-170f2e502c02"}, {"type": "text", "text": "-- bucket.lua: atomic token-bucket consume.\n-- KEYS[1]   = bucket key\n-- ARGV[1]   = capacity\n-- ARGV[2]   = refill per second\n-- ARGV[3]   = cost\n--\n-- The function returns {allowed (0/1), remaining tokens (int)}.\n--\n-- Stored state at KEYS[1] is a hash with fields:\n--   tokens : last observed bucket level (float, stored as string)\n--   ts     : Redis-server wall clock at last update (ms, integer)\n--\n-- Atomicity: this script runs as a single Redis command (EVALSHA), so\n-- the refill + consume sequence is not interleaved with any other\n-- client's evalsha against the same key. Reproducing the same logic\n-- as a sequence of GET + SET commands from the Python client would\n-- not be safe, even though Redis itself is single-threaded; the\n-- network round trips between separate commands open a race window.\n\nlocal key      = KEYS[1]\nlocal capacity = tonumber(ARGV[1])\nlocal refill   = tonumber(ARGV[2])\nlocal cost     = tonumber(ARGV[3])\n\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n\nlocal state = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\n-- Set TTL so unused buckets expire (10x time to fully refill, plus a floor)\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n", "id": "lc_fea41992-2631-4b3d-800f-214bd54dc4fe"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "71fdeb5c-8291-4480-968e-62ab02c7aaf0", "tool_call_id": "call_370daaff3e07457182bfd276", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:19:16.370931+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here is a full step-by-step explanation of `Limiter.check()`, covering both the Python wrapper and the Redis Lua script it executes.\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\n```python\ndef check(self, key: str, cost: int = 1) -> Tuple[bool, int]\n```\n\n| Parameter | Type | Default | Purpose |\n|-----------|------|---------|---------|\n| `key` | `str` | — | An arbitrary string identifying the rate-limited subject (e.g. user ID, IP, API path). |\n| `cost` | `int` | `1` | How many tokens this request should consume from the bucket. |\n\n## Return value\n\nA 2-tuple `(allowed, remaining)`:\n\n| Element | Type | Meaning |\n|---------|------|---------|\n| `allowed` | `bool` | `True` if the bucket had ≥ `cost` tokens (request permitted); `False` otherwise. |\n| `remaining` | `int` | Integer floor of tokens left in the bucket *after* this call (regardless of whether the request was allowed). |\n\n---\n\n## Step-by-step execution\n\n### 1 — Python: build the Redis key\n\n```python\nbucket_key = f\"rl:{{{key}}}\"\n```\n\nThe key is prefixed with `rl:` and wrapped in `{…}` braces. The braces are a Redis Cluster **hash-tag** — everything inside them is used for hash-slot routing, so all operations on the same logical key land on the same cluster shard.\n\n### 2 — Python: invoke the Lua script atomically\n\n```python\nresult = self._r.evalsha(self._sha, 1, bucket_key, str(self._capacity), str(self._refill), str(cost))\n```\n\n`EVALSHA` runs the pre-loaded Lua script as **a single Redis command**. This guarantees atomicity: no other client can interleave reads or writes against the same key between the refill and the consume.\n\nThe four `ARGV` values passed are capacity, refill rate (per second), and cost — all converted to strings for the Redis protocol.\n\n### 3 — Lua: read the server wall-clock time\n\n```lua\nlocal now_ms = redis.call(\"TIME\")\nnow_ms = now_ms[1] * 1000 + math.floor(now_ms[2] / 1000)\n```\n\n`TIME` returns `[seconds, microseconds]`. The script converts this to a **millisecond** timestamp. Using the server clock (not the client clock) avoids clock-skew problems across multiple app servers.\n\n### 4 — Lua: load existing bucket state (or initialise)\n\n```lua\nlocal state = redis.call(\"HMGET\", key, \"tokens\", \"ts\")\nlocal tokens = tonumber(state[1])\nlocal last_ts = tonumber(state[2])\n\nif tokens == nil or last_ts == nil then\n    tokens = capacity\n    last_ts = now_ms\nend\n```\n\nThe bucket is stored as a **Redis Hash** with two fields:\n* `tokens` — the last known token level (float, stored as a string).\n* `ts` — the server-wall-clock timestamp of the last update (ms, integer).\n\nIf the key does not exist yet (first-ever call for this `key`), the bucket is **initialised full** at `capacity` with `last_ts = now_ms`.\n\n### 5 — Lua: refill tokens based on elapsed time\n\n```lua\nlocal elapsed_sec = math.max(0, (now_ms - last_ts) / 1000.0)\ntokens = math.min(capacity, tokens + elapsed_sec * refill)\n```\n\nThe classic **token-bucket refill**: tokens accumulate at a rate of `refill_per_sec` for each elapsed second, clamped at `capacity` so the bucket never overflows.\n\n### 6 — Lua: attempt to consume\n\n```lua\nlocal allowed = 0\nif tokens >= cost then\n    tokens = tokens - cost\n    allowed = 1\nend\n```\n\nIf the (now-refilled) level is at least `cost`, the tokens are deducted and `allowed` is set to `1`. Otherwise the bucket is **not modified** (no tokens are withdrawn) and `allowed` stays `0`. This is important: a rejected request does **not** drain the bucket further.\n\n### 7 — Lua: persist the updated state\n\n```lua\nredis.call(\"HMSET\", key, \"tokens\", tostring(tokens), \"ts\", tostring(now_ms))\nlocal ttl = math.max(60, math.ceil(capacity / refill * 10))\nredis.call(\"EXPIRE\", key, ttl)\n```\n\nTwo Redis side effects:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---------|--------------|\n| `HMSET` | Overwrites both hash fields (`tokens` and `ts`) with the new values, whether the request was allowed or not. |\n| `EXPIRE` | Sets a TTL on the key so idle buckets are eventually garbage-collected. The TTL is `max(60 s, 10 × time_to_refill_from_empty)`. |\n\nBecause `EVALSHA` is atomic, these writes are visible to every other client only after the script finishes.\n\n### 8 — Lua: return the result\n\n```lua\nreturn {allowed, math.floor(tokens)}\n```\n\nReturns a two-element array: the `allowed` flag (`0` or `1`) and the integer floor of remaining tokens.\n\n### 9 — Python: unpack and return\n\n```python\nallowed = bool(result[0])    # 0/1 → False/True\nremaining = int(result[1])   # floor of remaining tokens\nreturn allowed, remaining\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Redis side effects per call\n\n1. **Creates or overwrites** the hash at key `rl:{<key>}` with fields `tokens` (stringified float) and `ts` (stringified millisecond timestamp).\n2. **Resets the TTL** of that key to at least 60 seconds and at most 10× the full-refill period.\n\nBoth the token mutation and the TTL reset happen atomically inside the Lua script, so there is no race window even under concurrent access.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1663, "prompt_tokens": 7526, "total_tokens": 9189, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 364, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 6528, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0019044408, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0004576308, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00144681}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780964307-uj0WB0SouWuo7Q3EsITI", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "n